{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514350"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12309"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.11,0.03,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4830"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63488"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the clinic with a history of psychosis, characterised by auditory hallucinations and delusions. He has been on an antipsychotic medication for the past six months and a good improvement in his symptoms. However, over the past few weeks, he has noticed the onset of involuntary movements in his face, including twitching and grimacing. He is concerned about these movements and reports that they have been causing him embarrassment in public.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antipsychotic medications is most commonly associated with his presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aripiprazole","Clozapine","Risperidone","Quetiapine","Haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing tardive dyskinesia, an extrapyramidal side effect characterised by involuntary movements. The antipsychotic medication that is most likely to be associated with the onset of tardive dyskinesia in this patient is\u003Cstrong\u003E haloperidol. \u003C/strong\u003ETardive dyskinesia is a well-known side effect of \u0022typical\u0022 or \u0022first generation\u0022 antipsychotic medications, such as haloperidol, which work by competitive blockade of dopamine D2 receptors in the brain. The risk of tardive dyskinesia increases with prolonged use of these medications and can persist even after the medication is discontinued.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole, clozapine, risperidone \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Equetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E are \u0022atypical\u0022 or \u0022second generation\u0022 antipsychotic medications. Compared to typical antipsychotics, atypical antipsychotics have lower affinity and occupancy for the dopaminergic receptors and a high degree of occupancy of the serotoninergic receptors. Because of this, atypical antipsychotics have much lower rates of extrapyramidal side effects, especially tardive dyskinesia. Of the atypical antipsychotics, clozapine and quetiapine are the least likely to cause abnormal movements overall, so are often used in patients with comorbid movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Typical antipsychotic drugs are associated with extrapyramidal symptoms, especially tardive dyskinesia.","Tardive dyskinesia is a serious and often irreversible side effect of long-term antipsychotic use.","Atypical antipsychotics have a lower risk of causing tardive dyskinesia compared to typical antipsychotics."],"references":["Chokhawala K, Stevens L. Antipsychotic Medications. 2023 Feb 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30137788. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30137788/","Satterthwaite TD, Wolf DH, Rosenheck RA, Gur RE, Caroff SN. A meta-analysis of the risk of acute extrapyramidal symptoms with intramuscular antipsychotics for the treatment of agitation. J Clin Psychiatry. 2008 Dec;69(12):1869-79. doi: 10.4088/jcp.v69n1204. Epub 2008 Dec 2. PMID: 19192477; PMCID: PMC4041731. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4041731/","D\u0027Souza RS, Hooten WM. Extrapyramidal Symptoms. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534115/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63488"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12309"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63488"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T12:41:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T12:42:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4830"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"me